{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}} {{Use Indian English|date=June 2018}} {{about|a research institution in India||Institute of Physics (disambiguation)}} {{Infobox University |name = Institute of Physics, Bhubaneswar |native_name = ପଦାର୍ଥ ବିଜ୍ଞାନ ଅନୁଷ୍ଠାନ |native_name_lang = or |image = |motto = |head_label = Director |head = Sudhakar Panda |type = [[Public University|Public]] |established = 1972 |city = [[Bhubaneswar]] |state = [[Odisha]] |country = [[India]] |undergrad = |postgrad = |faculty = |campus = |website = {{URL|http://www.iopb.res.in/}} |logo = Institute of Physics, Bhubaneswar (emblem).jpg }}
'''Institute of Physics, Bhubaneswar''' ({{lang-or|[[:or:ପଦାର୍ଥ_ବିଜ୍ଞାନ_ଅନୁଷ୍ଠାନ|'''ପଦାର୍ଥ ବିଜ୍ଞାନ ଅନୁଷ୍ଠାନ''']]}}) is an autonomous research institution of the [[Department of Atomic Energy (India)|Department of Atomic Energy]] (DAE), Government of [[India]].<ref name=dae>{{cite web|url=http://www.dae.gov.in/ni/nisep02/iop.htm|title=Institute of Physics: A Profile|author=Dr. R. K. Chaudhary|accessdate=2009-10-25}}</ref> The Institute was founded by Professor [[Bidhu Bhusan Das]], who was Director of Public Instruction, Odisha, at that time. Das set up the institute in 1972, supported by the Government of [[Odisha]] under the patronage of Odisha's education minister Banamali Patnaik, and chose Dr. Trilochan Pradhan as its first director, when the Institute started theoretical research programs in the various branches of physics.<ref name=dae/> Other notable physicists in the Institute's early days included Prof. T. P. Das, of [[SUNY]], Albany, New York, USA and Prof. Jagdish Mohanty of the Indian Institute of Technology, [[IIT Kanpur]] and [[Australian National University]], Canberra. In 1981, the Institute moved to its present campus near Chandrasekharpur, [[Bhubaneswar]]. It was taken over by the [[Department of Atomic Energy]], India on 25 March 1985 and started functioning as an autonomous body.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iopb.res.in/overview.php|title=Overview|accessdate=2009-10-25}}</ref>
==Research== [[File:IOP Bhubaneswar library.JPG|thumb|200px|IOPB library]] The institute conducts research in [[theoretical physics|theoretical]] and [[experimental physics|experimental]] [[physics]].
===Theoretical physics=== Research areas in theoretical physics include [[condensed matter theory]], [[nuclear physics|nuclear]] and [[particle physics|high energy physics]]. High-energy theorists at IOP have made contributions to [[field theory (physics)|field theories]], [[phase transitions]] in early universe, [[cosmology]], the [[Planck scale]] phenomena, [[string theory]] and high-energy nuclear physics such as qgp, equation of state and nuclear astrophysics, neutron stars, high-energy [[Phenomenology (particle physics)|phenomenology]] and neutrino physics phenomenology.<ref name=dae/> In theoretical condensed matter physics, research is centered on disordered systems, [[magnetism]], [[superconductivity]], low-dimensional systems, [[statistical physics]], strongly correlated systems, [[phase transitions]], [[Cluster (physics)|clusters]] and [[nanomaterials]].<ref name=dae/>
===Experimental physics=== [[File:Ion beam lab IOPB.jpg|thumb|200px|The Ion Beam Laboratory at IOP]] The experimental physics group encompasses accelerator-based research for advanced chemical and radioisotope analysis. The ion beam laboratory (IBL) is equipped with a 3MV [[tandem accelerator]] (NEC 9SDH-2).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iopb.res.in/ibl.php#1|title=Experimental Facilities, Institute of Physics, Bhubaneswar|accessdate=2009-10-25}}</ref> Research at the IBL includes [[Rutherford scattering|Rutherford back scattering]],[[Particle-induced X-ray emission]], accelerator [[mass spectrometry]], [[Channelling (physics)|channeling]], ion implantation, surface modification and characterization, microbeam analysis and [[nuclear reaction]] studies.{{fact|date=June 2018}}
The 3 million volt NEC 9SDH-2 pelletron accelerator of the Accelerator Mass Spectrometry lab is a multi-disciplinary research accelerator for various physics experiments.<ref name=ams>{{cite web|url=http://www.iopb.res.in/~ams/|title=AMS Homepage|accessdate=2009-10-25}}</ref> The experimental facilities available in the ion beam laboratory include an [[accelerator mass spectrometry]] (AMS) for [[radiocarbon dating]], micro-beam facility and an external beam facility.<ref name=ams/> Other experimental facilities include an ESCA ([[electron spectroscopy]] for chemical analysis), HRTEM (high resolution transmission [[electron microscope]]), MBE ([[molecular beam epitaxy]]), cluster generator and [[Nanotechnology|nano material]] research facility.{{fact|date=June 2018}}
==Education==
The Institute runs regular pre-doctoral ([[Master of Philosophy]]) and doctoral ([[PhD.]]) programs for postgraduate students of physics. The course work is planned to emphasize doctoral research and teaching skills.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianstudentsforum.com/admissions/institute-of-physics-bhubaneswar-phd-admission-2009/|title=Institute of Physics, Bhubaneswar - PhD. Admissions|accessdate=2009-10-25}}</ref>
