{{distinguish|University of São Paulo}} {{Infobox University |name= São Paulo State University |native_name= Universidade Estadual Paulista "Júlio de Mesquita Filho" |native_name_lang = Pt |other_name = UNESP |image= Logo Unesp.svg |established=1976 |type=[[Public university]] system |rector=Sandro Roberto Valentini <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www2.unesp.br/portal#!/reitor/|title=UNESP: Reitoria - Portal da Universidade|work=unesp.br|accessdate=6 September 2018}}</ref> |state= [[São Paulo (state)|São Paulo]] |country= [[Brazil]] |budget = [[Brazilian real|R$]]1.496 billion<ref name=Factsheet>{{cite web|title=Universidade Estadual Paulista – UNESP |url=http://www.unesp.br/apresentacao/perfil.php|accessdate=30 October 2010}}</ref> |students = 47,917<ref name=Factsheet /> |undergrad= 35,284<ref name=Factsheet /> |postgrad= 12,633<ref name=Factsheet /> |academic_staff = 3,316<ref name=Factsheet /> |administrative_staff = 7,138<ref name=Factsheet /> |affiliations = [[Compostela Group of Universities]] |website=[http://www.unesp.br unesp.br] |city = [[Araçatuba]], [[Araraquara]], [[Assis]], [[Bauru]], [[Botucatu]], [[Dracena]], [[Franca]], [[Guaratinguetá]], [[Ilha Solteira]], [[Itapeva, São Paulo|Itapeva]], [[Jaboticabal]], [[Marília]], [[Ourinhos]], [[Presidente Prudente, São Paulo|Presidente Prudente]], [[Registro]], [[Rio Claro, São Paulo|Rio Claro]], [[Rosana, São Paulo|Rosana]], [[São João da Boa Vista]], [[São José do Rio Preto]], [[São José dos Campos]], [[São Paulo]], [[Santos, São Paulo|Santos]], [[Sorocaba]] and [[Tupã, São Paulo|Tupã]] }} '''São Paulo State University''' ({{lang-pt|Universidade Estadual Paulista "Júlio de Mesquita Filho"}}, '''UNESP''') is one of the six public [[University|universities]] of the [[Brazil]]ian [[States of Brazil|state of]] [[São Paulo (state)|São Paulo]] (the others are [[University of São Paulo|USP]], [[São Paulo State Technological Faculty|FATEC]], [[Universidade Estadual de Campinas|UNICAMP]], [[Universidade Federal do ABC|UFABC]], [[Universidade Federal de São Paulo|UNIFESP]] and [[UFSCar]]). UNESP is part of the state’s higher education system and the only Brazilian member of the [[Compostela Group of Universities]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www2.usc.es/gcompostela/en/menu_superior/members/index.html|title=CGU Members|website=www2.usc.es|access-date=2018-09-06}}</ref>
UNESP has a combined student body of over 45,000 spread among its 23 campuses. The first of them is the Araraquara Pharmacy and Odontology Faculty, founded in 1923 and incorporated by the state of São Paulo in 1956. Before the university’s official foundation in 1976, its original 12 campuses were public independent faculties.
With a budget of R$2.6 billion in 2015, UNESP currently has 33 teaching, research and extension units in 23 campuses spread across inland and coastal cities, as well as in the city of São Paulo. It also has 30 libraries, two hospitals, three animal hospitals, five farms and seven complementary units.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.feg.unesp.br/Home/PaginasPessoais/profsalomon/unesp.pdf|title=Presentation about UNESP|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>{{Additional citation needed|date=August 2018}}
São Paulo State University is considered the sixth most important university in Brazil, according to the Ranking Universitário Folha,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ruf.folha.uol.com.br/rankings/universidades/universidade-estadual-paulista-julio-de-mesquita-filho-8401.shtml|title=Ranking Universitário Folha|work=uol.com.br|accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref> ninth most important university in the [[QS World University Rankings#QS Latin American University Rankings|QS Latin American University Rankings]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/latin-american-university-rankings/2014#sorting=rank+region=+country=+faculty=+stars=false+search=|title=QS University Rankings: Latin America 2014|work=Top Universities|accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref> It is ranked amongst the 300 best universities in the world as of the "[[Academic Ranking of World Universities]] - 2012<ref>http://www.shanghairanking.com/Institution.jsp?param=Sao%20Paulo%20State%20University</ref> and third best in the [[QS World University Ranking#Brics 2014]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/brics-rankings/2014#sorting=rank+country=+stars=false+search=|title=QS University Rankings: BRICS 2014|work=Top Universities|accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref>
== History ==
Universities in Brazil are a recent phenomenon, compared to other Latin American countries. The first one was created in 1808 (Rio de Janeiro Medicine Faculty). Before the 20th century, there were no universities in the country. Existing institutions in higher education were either public or church-run independent institutes.{{Citation needed|date=August 2018}}
[[Universidade Federal do Rio de Janeiro|Rio de Janeiro Federal University]] was the first one, containing every faculty inside Rio de Janeiro city in 1926. São Paulo’s first university was [[University of São Paulo|USP]], founded in 1933. By the 1950s, countryside people had to move toward capitals for undergraduate study. There were few higher education institutes outside Brazilian metropolises then.{{Citation needed|date=August 2018}}
[[São Paulo state government]] created many colleges outside the capital in the 1950s and 1960s. Prominent cities in the state received these isolated institutes, known as “Faculdade de Filosofia”.{{Citation needed|date=August 2018}}
In the 1970s, discussions were made within state government on how to coordinate the separate institutes. One Suggestions was to join the 14 institutes in a federation or a single university, which was enacted on subsequently.{{Citation needed|date=August 2018}}
Inspired by the [[University of California]] multi-campus system, UNESP was founded in 1976. The original campuses were in [[Araçatuba]], [[Araraquara]], [[Assis]], [[Botucatu]], [[Franca]], [[Guaratinguetá]], [[Ilha Solteira]], [[Jaboticabal]], [[Marília]], [[Presidente Prudente, São Paulo|Presidente Prudente]], [[Rio Claro, São Paulo|Rio Claro]], [[São José dos Campos]], [[São José do Rio Preto]] and São Paulo. [[Bauru]] campus was incorporated in 1988.{{Citation needed|date=August 2018}}
The name "Universidade Estadual Paulista" was suggested by the first rector of UNESP, Professor Luiz Ferreira Martins, and the name "Júlio de Mesquita Filho" was suggested by Prof. Dr. Moacyr Expedito Marret Vaz Guimarães, then President of the State Council of Education (EEC).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ict.unesp.br/#!/instituicao/memorias/biografias/luis-ferreira-martins/|title=UNESP: Câmpus de São José dos Campos - Instituto de Ciência e Tecnologia|website=www.ict.unesp.br|access-date=2018-08-09}}</ref>
== Facilities == [[File:Unesp_Marília.jpg|thumb|Campus Marília]]UNESP has a total of 1,900 laboratories and 30 libraries, which together have around 900,000 books available.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www2.unesp.br/portal#!/international/about-unesp/libraries|title=Unesp - Universidade Estadual Paulista - Portal|website=www2.unesp.br|access-date=2018-08-15}}</ref>{{Additional citation needed|date=August 2018}}
In addition the facilities encompass museums, gardens, parks, botanical gardens and five experimental farms, totaling an area of 62.8 million m², of which 745.4 thousand m² are developed area.
The university also owns the Hospital de Clínicas de Botucatu and manages the State Hospital of Bauru, which together have around 800 beds, as well as veterinary hospitals and dentistry, psychology, speech therapy and physiotherapy clinics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www2.unesp.br/portal#!/international/about-unesp/history|title=Unesp - Universidade Estadual Paulista - Portal|website=www2.unesp.br|access-date=2018-08-15}}</ref>{{Additional citation needed|date=August 2018}}[[File:SaoPaulo_RedeUNESP.svg|thumb|Map of the state of São Paulo with districts that are home to a campus of UNESP.]][[File:Unesp_Campus_Marília.jpg|thumb|Campus Marília]]
